<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-713-821  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 713 821.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  Dec 10 1990 v7 n15 p101(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Optical drive development spans decades of growth: from videolaserdiscs to today's erasable optical. (overview to five reviewsof optical disk drives)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Koontz, Charles P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The optical disk technology of the 1990s has its roots intechnology developed for the consumer electronics market in the1970s.andP;  The process used to produce laser videodiscs in the '70sis still used to produce CD-ROM and CD audio disks.andP;  The erasableoptical drives of the '90s use a modulated laser to heat thesurface of a disk coated with a magnetic reflective material,creating tiny spots with different magnetic and reflectiveproperties, forming the ones and zeros of digital data recording.andO;A magnetic field is used to erase the spots.andP;  Erasable opticaldrives were intended as a replacement for magnetic drives becauseof greater density.andP;  Recent improvements to magnetic media haveeliminated much of the advantage, and optical drives, which areslower and more expensive, must somehow compensate to maintaincompetitiveness.andP;  Adding a compression algorithm to improveoptical drive speed or adding disk caching are two possiblemethods to improve optical drive performance, although compressionalgorithm standards need to be developed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Erasable Optical MemoryMethodsStorage CapacityPerformance ImprovementComparison.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Executive summary. (table)Optical drive scoring. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>